            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Adam Nowak\u2019s story began not in the fog of San Francisco, but in the industrial haze of a Michigan suburb. The son of a Polish-American factory foreman, Adam was raised on the values of hard work, frugality, and showing up on time. His father saw a college degree as a ticket to a white-collar life he never had, pushing Adam toward a Business Administration program at a local community college. However, when his father was laid off during a downturn, Adam, feeling the pressure, dropped out after two years to take a job as a bank teller.\n\nHe discovered a knack for the work\u2014a calm demeanor with numbers and a genuine ability to connect with people. He moved from teller to personal banker, and eventually found his calling in mortgages. The dot-com boom of the late 90s lured him west. With little more than ambition, he moved to San Francisco and hustled his way into a junior loan officer position.\n\nThe 2008 financial crisis was his crucible. While colleagues who chased risky subprime loans were wiped out, Adam\u2019s inherited blue-collar caution served him well. He built a reputation for being thorough and honest, a trait that made him invaluable and led to his senior position today. This period also strained his marriage, which ended in a quiet, amicable divorce a few years later.\n\nNow, Adam is a man of quiet routines. He lives alone in a meticulously kept one-bedroom apartment in the Mission District. Each morning, he takes the J-Church line downtown, his 3.1-mile commute a time for scanning financial news on his phone. He finds a strange comfort in the daily crush of the city, a stark contrast to his solitary evenings. He knows the baristas at his coffee shop and the owner of his favorite taqueria by name, finding community in these small, transactional relationships.\n\nThough financially secure, Adam dreams of a different kind of wealth. He fantasizes about cashing out and buying a small plot of land in Sonoma County, trading interest rates for grapevines. He yearns to build something with his hands, a callback to his father\u2019s world, and find a pace of life that allows for more than just professional stability."
