            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the silence in the Michigan kitchen after his father told him about the layoff. It was 1996. His dad, a man built like the machines he ran, just stared at his calloused hands on the table, looking smaller than Adam had ever seen him. In that quiet, Adam felt the weight of his father\u2019s dream for him become his own responsibility. He decided then to leave school. It wasn't failure; it was the first time he truly understood the cost of things, a lesson that would become his professional bedrock.\n\n2.\nHis first successful job interview in San Francisco, late 1998. He stood at the window of a high-rise in the Financial District, looking down as the fog rolled in, swallowing the streets below. He felt like a complete imposter in his ill-fitting suit. But watching the city lights begin to glitter through the haze, a fierce, terrifying ambition surged through him. He wasn't just chasing a job; he was trying to claim a tiny, sparkling piece of this impossible place for himself.\n\n3.\nFall, 2008. He sat in a young couple's living room, children\u2019s drawings taped to the walls, explaining why their mortgage was resetting. He was calm, professional, but their quiet desperation felt like a physical force. He saw the ghosts of his own parents in their faces. While his careful practices saved his career during the crash, this moment cemented why. He wasn't just moving numbers; he was a custodian of people's stability, a responsibility he would carry with a somber, almost reverent, weight.\n\n4.\nThe last day in the apartment he\u2019d shared with his wife, in 2012. After the last box was gone, they stood by the door. She handed him her key, and they managed a sad, tired smile. Then she left. He remembered locking the door and hearing the bolt click home in the profound silence. The quiet wasn\u2019t peaceful; it was a vast, empty space. It was then he learned the difference between being alone and being lonely, a distinction he\u2019s navigated ever since.\n\n5.\nA Saturday last spring, on a drive through Sonoma. He\u2019d pulled over by a vineyard, got out of his car, and crumbled a clump of dry, red earth in his hand. The dirt felt more real, more substantial, than any contract he\u2019d ever signed. The sun on his face, the smell of the soil\u2014it wasn't just a nice view. It was the sudden, sharp realization of another kind of wealth, one measured in dirt under the fingernails, not interest rates. The dream of a different life was planted in that instant."
